        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs — uncertainty bounds documented and propagated",
        "description": "All model input parameters must have documented sources and uncertainty ranges. Uncertainty propagation through Latin Hypercube Sampling (≥ 500 samples) required. The power-law exponent alpha is explicitly flagged as having wide uncertainty (±12%, literature range 0.62–0.85); this gap is documented and its impact on NIH bounded. Gradation 2 requires documented input uncertainty; wide bounds are acceptable provided they are honestly reported and propagated."
      },
      "rationale": "Model inputs assessed at Gradation 2. Key inputs (blood viscosity ±8%, power-law exponent alpha ±12%, inlet velocity profile ±5%) are documented with literature-sourced uncertainty ranges. The power-law exponent alpha carries the widest uncertainty (±12%) due to inter-study variability in published hemolysis damage models; this is explicitly flagged as a known epistemic gap. LHS propagation (500 samples) quantifies the resulting NIH uncertainty as ±0.031 mg/100 L (k=2). Despite the wide alpha uncertainty, the worst-case NIH prediction remains below the RH < 1 threshold with 97.3% probability across the sampled space, supporting the acceptance decision. The gap is documented honestly and accepted as residual risk consistent with MRL 2 expectations for a medium-influence model."
